            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers the steam from the saucepan fogging up their small NOPA kitchen window. Raj, then her husband of a year, was patiently showing her how to crush cardamom pods for his mother\u2019s chai recipe. The scent of ginger and cinnamon filled the air. In that moment, her practical world of spreadsheets and timelines melted into his vibrant one of spice and story. It wasn't just about tea; it was about building a new \"us,\" a home that smelled of both their traditions. That warmth became her foundation.\n\n2.\nThe morning after Raj died, the silence in the apartment was a physical weight. She was 39. Kai, only seven, asked why Dad wasn\u2019t making his oatmeal. Tamara recalls her breath catching, her entire world a raw nerve. But she looked at her son\u2019s trusting face, took out the bread for his sandwich, and cut the crusts off, just like always. In that simple, mechanical act, her grief was forged into a shield. From that moment on, her purpose was singular: be the stability he had lost.\n\n3.\nShe was 43 when a multi-million dollar project almost imploded. The lead consultant, a prodigy from Stanford, was panicking in the conference room. Tamara recalls quietly locating the missing data on an old server, rerouting the international shipments, and rescheduling the client call, all before her second cup of coffee. The consultant got the glory, but in the quiet hum of the solved problem, she felt her own power solidify. She wasn\u2019t just supporting brilliance; she was the platform it stood on. It was then she knew her worth.\n\n4.\nGolden Gate Park, a year after Raj was gone. Kai, age eight, wobbled on his two-wheeler, his face a mask of terror and determination. Tamara ran alongside him, her hand on the seat, her lungs burning. She remembers the exact moment she let go. He shouted, half in fear, half in triumph, as he pedaled away from her under his own power. Watching him, she felt a sharp pang of Raj\u2019s absence mixed with a fierce, swelling pride. She could do this. She could launch their son into the world alone.\n\n5.\nShe remembers the drive home from Santa Cruz last fall, after moving Kai into his dorm. The car felt cavernous, the passenger seat achingly empty. She passed the coastal artichoke fields, the setting sun glinting off the windshield. There were no tears, just a profound quiet. The intense, eighteen-year project of raising him was complete. For the first time since her twenties, the future wasn't about someone else's needs, but a blank page waiting for her own. The feeling was both terrifying and utterly liberating."
